1. Project Overview
This project documents the investigation of suspected Lateral Movement within a Windows Domain environment (soprano.local). The objective was to identify unauthorized service account logons on the Primary Domain Controller (DC.soprano.local) that could indicate an attacker establishing persistence or moving between systems.

2. The Challenge: UI Limitations
During the investigation, the standard Windows Event Viewer GUI was inconsistent, frequently failing to apply XML filters and throwing "Query Error" messages. To bypass these technical hurdles and process the high volume of security logs (18,000+ events), I utilized PowerShell scripting to perform deep packet/log inspection.

3. Investigative Logic
I focused specifically on Event ID 4624 (Successful Logon). While this ID is common, the key to identifying lateral movement is the Logon Type.

Logon Type 2 (Interactive): Standard keyboard/screen login.

Logon Type 3 (Network): Accessing shared folders or printers.

Logon Type 5 (Service): Indicates a service starting up.

Attackers often create malicious services to run code in the background. Finding a Logon Type 5 associated with a human user account or an unknown service name is a high-fidelity indicator of compromise.

4. Automation via PowerShell
The following script was developed to parse the Security log, convert the raw data into XML for field accessibility, and extract only the unique service-based logons.

PowerShell
# Filter for Successful Logons (4624) and extract Service Logons (Type 5)
Get-WinEvent -FilterHashtable @{LogName='Security';ID=4624} | foreach {
    $xml = [xml]$_.ToXml()
    $logonType = $xml.Event.EventData.Data | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "LogonType"}
    $user = $xml.Event.EventData.Data | Where-Object {$_.Name -eq "TargetUserName"}
    
    if ($logonType.'#text' -eq "5") {
        [PSCustomObject]@{
            Time = $_.TimeCreated
            User = $user.'#text'
            Type = $logonType.'#text'
        }
    }
} | Select-Object -Unique User, Time
5. Findings
By filtering the noise of standard system accounts (SYSTEM, NETWORK SERVICE), I was able to isolate unique account logons on the Domain Controller.

Machine Account Logs: Observed SOPRANOS-DC$ logging in as SYSTEM. While high-privilege, this was verified as standard OS behavior for the Domain Controller.

Lateral Movement Indicators: By focusing on the TargetUserName field, any account mismatch (e.g., a standard user account logging in as a service) was flagged for further process-level analysis.

6. Conclusion
This investigation highlights the importance of Logon Type analysis in detecting advanced threats. Using PowerShell for log analysis allowed for a faster, more reliable forensic process compared to traditional GUI methods, enabling the identification of the "Subject" vs "Target" relationship within the Domain Controller's security logs.
